1
00:00:41,841 --> 00:00:44,810
- I used to love
my dad's stories,

2
00:00:44,844 --> 00:00:49,679
until the one he told me
on my tenth birthday.

3
00:00:49,716 --> 00:00:51,946
- There once was a kingdom

4
00:00:51,985 --> 00:00:55,648
where everybody lived forever.

5
00:00:55,688 --> 00:00:58,680
But the problem
with nobody ever dying

6
00:00:58,725 --> 00:01:01,660
was that the kingdom
got very crowded.

7
00:01:01,694 --> 00:01:02,922
And so the king,

8
00:01:02,962 --> 00:01:05,157
getting squeezed out
of his own castle

9
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:07,530
by his endless royal lineage,

10
00:01:07,567 --> 00:01:09,501
issued a decree.

11
00:01:09,536 --> 00:01:11,663
- Everybody in my kingdom,

12
00:01:11,704 --> 00:01:15,538
please pick one person
from your family to die.

13
00:01:15,575 --> 00:01:17,668
We will have a mass execution

14
00:01:17,710 --> 00:01:19,940
that will bring forth
much-needed space.

15
00:01:19,979 --> 00:01:21,503
Sorry to bum everybody out,

16
00:01:21,548 --> 00:01:23,982
but that's the way it goes.

17
00:01:24,017 --> 00:01:26,850
-And each family showed up
with their martyr,

18
00:01:26,886 --> 00:01:28,979
all except one family.

19
00:01:29,022 --> 00:01:31,149
- Sire, we can't decide.

20
00:01:31,191 --> 00:01:32,590
We love each other so much

21
00:01:32,625 --> 00:01:34,889
that we would all like
to die together.

22
00:01:34,928 --> 00:01:37,192
- Oh, no, they can't all die.

23
00:01:37,230 --> 00:01:38,822
They run the bakery.

24
00:01:38,865 --> 00:01:41,766
They make the best cinnamon buns
in all the land.

25
00:01:41,801 --> 00:01:44,133
- What if we each cut off
a piece of ourselves?

26
00:01:44,170 --> 00:01:46,365
And with all of these pieces
combined,

27
00:01:46,406 --> 00:01:49,534
it will be as if one less person
lived in town.

28
00:01:49,576 --> 00:01:51,737
- Interesting.
Hmm.

29
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:53,336
Continue.

30
00:01:53,379 --> 00:01:56,314
- But the daughter refused.

31
00:01:56,349 --> 00:01:59,944
- [sighs]
But, Dad, I like my limbs.

32
00:01:59,986 --> 00:02:01,510
- Don't be selfish.

33
00:02:01,554 --> 00:02:03,715
Would you rather
one of us die?

34
00:02:03,756 --> 00:02:04,916
- You can have my arm.

35
00:02:04,958 --> 00:02:06,619
- I'll give my right ear.

36
00:02:06,659 --> 00:02:09,025
- I see no problem
losing some of my fingers.

37
00:02:09,062 --> 00:02:10,654
- I'll throw in my nose.

38
00:02:10,697 --> 00:02:13,257
- Guarantee me a leg,

39
00:02:13,299 --> 00:02:14,789
and it's a deal.

40
00:02:14,834 --> 00:02:16,961
- Well, I do have another one.

41
00:02:17,003 --> 00:02:19,369
Okay, I'm in.

42
00:02:19,405 --> 00:02:20,838
- [laughing]

43
00:02:20,874 --> 00:02:23,570
- After the executioner
had done the deed,

44
00:02:23,610 --> 00:02:27,068
the family made
an unsightly sight

45
00:02:27,113 --> 00:02:29,274
and business went bad.

46
00:02:29,315 --> 00:02:32,910
So the family started selling
their cinnamon buns

47
00:02:32,952 --> 00:02:35,785
by mail order
to the next kingdom.

48
00:02:35,822 --> 00:02:37,756
And since no one
had to look at them,

49
00:02:37,790 --> 00:02:39,257
they were a huge hit,

50
00:02:39,292 --> 00:02:42,125
and they made heaps of dough.

51
00:02:43,429 --> 00:02:46,626
And the father said
to the daughter,

52
00:02:46,666 --> 00:02:50,261
"You see what we can accomplish
if we all stick together?"

53
00:02:54,774 --> 00:02:56,002
The end.

54
00:02:56,042 --> 00:02:59,068
- It was the last birthday party
I ever had.

55
00:02:59,112 --> 00:03:02,081
[brisk, whimsical music]

56
00:03:02,115 --> 00:03:08,213
♪ ♪

57
00:03:08,254 --> 00:03:10,085
There were two things I loved

58
00:03:10,123 --> 00:03:12,557
more than anything
in this world:

59
00:03:12,592 --> 00:03:16,119
running and math.

60
00:03:16,162 --> 00:03:17,595
My dad was a mathematician,

61
00:03:17,630 --> 00:03:20,531
so loving math
was loving my dad.

62
00:03:20,567 --> 00:03:23,627
- What is this?
What are you reading?

63
00:03:23,670 --> 00:03:25,604
Pre-calculus?
- Yep.

64
00:03:25,638 --> 00:03:28,232
We both found safety
in numbers.

65
00:03:28,274 --> 00:03:33,109
In my family,
1 plus 1 equaled 3.

66
00:03:33,146 --> 00:03:34,909
- I hope when you grow up
that you...

67
00:03:34,948 --> 00:03:38,179
- Life was good.

68
00:03:38,218 --> 00:03:40,049
My father was a track star
in college,

69
00:03:40,086 --> 00:03:43,146
and I dreamed of the day
that I would really and truly

70
00:03:43,189 --> 00:03:46,181
run faster than he did.

71
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:48,057
But on the last good day
my father had...

72
00:03:48,094 --> 00:03:49,083
Dad!

73
00:03:49,128 --> 00:03:50,720
Nobody won.

74
00:03:54,167 --> 00:03:56,192
What's the matter?

75
00:04:03,009 --> 00:04:07,070
That's when I started
to knock on wood.

76
00:04:07,113 --> 00:04:08,080
[knocking]

77
00:04:08,114 --> 00:04:09,342
Each knock was a number,

78
00:04:09,382 --> 00:04:11,907
and each number kept me safe.

79
00:04:13,419 --> 00:04:15,580
Without them, I'd be alone.

80
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:16,816
[knocking]

81
00:04:18,992 --> 00:04:19,959
Dad...

82
00:04:19,993 --> 00:04:21,790
They know how to fix a body,

83
00:04:21,828 --> 00:04:25,286
but would they be able
to fix his mind?

84
00:04:26,633 --> 00:04:28,999
My dad looked gray and gone,

85
00:04:29,035 --> 00:04:31,094
but I knew he was
in there somewhere,

86
00:04:31,137 --> 00:04:35,073
and I was determined
to get him back.

87
00:04:35,108 --> 00:04:37,406
So I made a deal
with the universe.

88
00:04:37,443 --> 00:04:39,911
I would give up everything
that I cared about,

89
00:04:39,946 --> 00:04:43,006
and the universe
would give me back my father.

90
00:04:44,884 --> 00:04:46,511
I quit dessert.

91
00:04:48,021 --> 00:04:49,010
[aerosol hissing]

92
00:04:49,055 --> 00:04:51,489
I quit going to movies.

93
00:04:53,459 --> 00:04:55,427
I quit my friends.

94
00:04:56,663 --> 00:04:58,290
I quit flipping
through atlases.

95
00:05:00,900 --> 00:05:03,562
I even quit running.

96
00:05:05,038 --> 00:05:06,437
The more I liked something,

97
00:05:06,472 --> 00:05:09,498
the more I needed to ruin it.

98
00:05:13,846 --> 00:05:18,647
The only thing I didn't quit
was numbers.

99
00:05:18,685 --> 00:05:21,210
[light knocking]

100
00:05:23,022 --> 00:05:26,583
If I could jump rope 43 times
without missing

101
00:05:26,626 --> 00:05:30,858
or if I could catch the ball
27 times in a row,

102
00:05:30,897 --> 00:05:33,229
if the number
of falling leaves I counted

103
00:05:33,266 --> 00:05:35,734
equaled the number of letters
in my dad's name,

104
00:05:35,768 --> 00:05:37,736
then maybe
I would get him back.

105
00:05:37,770 --> 00:05:39,670
I never stopped counting.

106
00:05:39,706 --> 00:05:41,401
I never stopped hoping.

107
00:05:41,441 --> 00:05:44,342
Numbers:

108
00:05:44,377 --> 00:05:47,471
safe,

109
00:05:47,513 --> 00:05:48,878
reliable,

110
00:05:48,915 --> 00:05:50,007
perfect.

111
00:05:50,049 --> 00:05:52,347
[chimes tinkling]

112
00:05:52,385 --> 00:05:54,353
Then suddenly,
my mother decided

113
00:05:54,387 --> 00:05:56,480
that three was one number
too many.

114
00:05:56,522 --> 00:05:58,581
- You're kicking me out?

115
00:05:59,926 --> 00:06:02,224
- You don't have friends.

116
00:06:02,261 --> 00:06:05,856
You don't have a job.

117
00:06:05,898 --> 00:06:07,957
[sighs]
It's time for you to go.

118
00:06:10,069 --> 00:06:11,696
- But I love it here.

119
00:06:11,738 --> 00:06:13,706
- You're lying, Mona.

120
00:06:13,740 --> 00:06:16,766
And what's worse is,
you don't even know it.

121
00:06:16,809 --> 00:06:19,869
I have to take care of him.

122
00:06:19,912 --> 00:06:21,607
You don't.

123
00:06:27,653 --> 00:06:30,884
[dog barking]

124
00:06:30,923 --> 00:06:33,687
- [coughing]

125
00:06:38,998 --> 00:06:40,260
By the third night,

126
00:06:40,299 --> 00:06:44,133
my math book and l
called it quits.

127
00:06:44,170 --> 00:06:48,004
- We can help you
with the first month's rent.

128
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:49,667
I've saved a little,

129
00:06:49,709 --> 00:06:53,270
and Dad has
his disability check.

130
00:06:55,882 --> 00:06:58,544
- She'll never find
an apartment

131
00:06:58,584 --> 00:07:01,644
with a toilet
as strong as ours.

132
00:07:01,687 --> 00:07:02,915
- [sighs]

133
00:07:04,757 --> 00:07:07,749
- [coughing roughly]

134
00:07:19,806 --> 00:07:22,798
Suddenly I knew
what infinity felt like.

135
00:07:27,313 --> 00:07:29,213
It was really long.

136
00:07:33,419 --> 00:07:36,354
[phone rings]

137
00:07:36,389 --> 00:07:37,651
- Mom?

138
00:07:37,690 --> 00:07:39,419
- Is this Mona Gray?

139
00:07:39,459 --> 00:07:40,448
- Yeah.

140
00:07:40,493 --> 00:07:42,154
- This is Ms. Gelband.

141
00:07:42,195 --> 00:07:44,595
I was your elementary school
principal.

142
00:07:44,630 --> 00:07:45,927
- Yeah?

143
00:07:45,965 --> 00:07:48,661
- Well, I just ran
into your mother

144
00:07:48,701 --> 00:07:50,328
in front of the bakery,

145
00:07:50,369 --> 00:07:52,963
and our math teacher,
Ms. Swordstrum,

146
00:07:53,005 --> 00:07:57,271
suddenly flew off to Paraguay
to become a revolutionary.

147
00:07:57,310 --> 00:07:59,437
So your mother jumped in

148
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:01,709
and told me
that you're living in town,

149
00:08:01,747 --> 00:08:03,738
that you don't have a job,

150
00:08:03,783 --> 00:08:05,512
but you have a college degree

151
00:08:05,551 --> 00:08:06,540
in math.

152
00:08:06,586 --> 00:08:08,178
You're it.
- It?

153
00:08:08,221 --> 00:08:09,779
- Our new math teacher.

154
00:08:09,822 --> 00:08:13,451
I remember at recess
when you were a child,

155
00:08:13,493 --> 00:08:16,053
while all the other kids
were playing kickball,

156
00:08:16,095 --> 00:08:19,292
you sat on the monkey bars
doing long division.

157
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:22,358
You're perfect for the job,
Mona Gray.

158
00:08:28,508 --> 00:08:30,840
- Why would you tell her
I had a math degree

159
00:08:30,877 --> 00:08:32,242
when I quit college?

160
00:08:32,278 --> 00:08:34,644
- You need to find a way
to pay rent.

161
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:36,671
- Why?

162
00:08:36,716 --> 00:08:38,013
You're the one
who kicked me out.

163
00:08:38,050 --> 00:08:39,517
- You might like teaching.

164
00:08:39,552 --> 00:08:41,520
- I'll hate it.

165
00:08:41,554 --> 00:08:43,249
[car door clicks open]

166
00:08:43,289 --> 00:08:47,316
- The welcome wagon
officially welcomes you!

167
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:52,263
We like to think of ourselves
as being ahead of the curve.

168
00:08:52,298 --> 00:08:55,699
One teacher for each subject.

169
00:08:55,735 --> 00:08:59,262
I guess that makes you
our very own Ms. Math.

170
00:08:59,305 --> 00:09:00,932
[laughs]

171
00:09:04,176 --> 00:09:07,668
We may want
to lighten up the decor,

172
00:09:07,713 --> 00:09:12,207
something cheery
and "math is fun"-ish.

173
00:09:16,889 --> 00:09:18,652
- You made a mistake.

174
00:09:18,691 --> 00:09:20,283
I'm not a teacher.

175
00:09:20,326 --> 00:09:21,315
I--

176
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:22,588
- There's an old saying:

177
00:09:22,628 --> 00:09:25,893
"No one is a teacher
until they're a teacher."

178
00:09:31,470 --> 00:09:35,429
- I had math in this room
with Mr. Jones.

179
00:09:37,076 --> 00:09:41,376
- 1, 2, 3,

180
00:09:41,414 --> 00:09:44,440
5, 8,

181
00:09:44,483 --> 00:09:49,386
13, 21...

182
00:09:49,422 --> 00:09:53,449
Who can tell me the next number
in this pattern?

183
00:09:55,561 --> 00:09:57,051
Miss Gray?

184
00:09:57,096 --> 00:09:58,563
- 34.

185
00:09:58,598 --> 00:10:02,796
- You are correct!

186
00:10:05,638 --> 00:10:09,631
- I never saw him without
a wax number around his neck.

187
00:10:14,380 --> 00:10:19,477
The numbers varied
according to his mood.

188
00:10:19,518 --> 00:10:21,952
He'd go higher
in a better mood,

189
00:10:21,988 --> 00:10:24,183
lower if he felt lower.

190
00:10:29,595 --> 00:10:34,692
I wondered if he had
the numbers my dad needed.

191
00:10:34,734 --> 00:10:38,295
To the world,
they were just numbers.

192
00:10:38,337 --> 00:10:42,330
But to us,
they were invisible signs.

193
00:10:52,852 --> 00:10:56,982
Mr. Jones quit teaching
and opened a hardware store.

194
00:10:57,023 --> 00:11:00,618
And I was the only one
who understood why.

195
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:02,719
He was trying
to get his numbers up.

196
00:11:10,870 --> 00:11:13,862
We don't talk anymore.

197
00:11:13,906 --> 00:11:17,899
- So can I count on you?

198
00:11:41,267 --> 00:11:43,235
[bell ringing]

199
00:11:43,269 --> 00:11:45,999
[children shouting]

200
00:11:46,038 --> 00:11:48,734
[footsteps clomping]

201
00:11:48,774 --> 00:11:53,177
- Hi, first graders.

202
00:11:53,212 --> 00:11:54,679
I'm Miss Gray.

203
00:11:54,714 --> 00:11:57,444
- Miss Gray, you're it!

204
00:11:57,483 --> 00:11:59,644
- Um--
Um, no.

205
00:11:59,685 --> 00:12:01,550
- Can we call you Mommy?

206
00:12:01,587 --> 00:12:03,054
- Oh!

207
00:12:03,089 --> 00:12:04,078
[bell ringing]

208
00:12:04,123 --> 00:12:05,613
Second graders,

209
00:12:05,658 --> 00:12:08,718
look at all the numbers
on the wall.

210
00:12:09,428 --> 00:12:12,022
Guys, please.

211
00:12:12,064 --> 00:12:15,056
[bell ringing]

212
00:12:19,038 --> 00:12:21,836
- No way!
Check it out!

213
00:12:21,874 --> 00:12:23,739
- Pretty awesome numbers.

214
00:12:23,776 --> 00:12:27,610
- I like the 2.

215
00:12:27,646 --> 00:12:30,410
I like the 9 a lot.

216
00:12:30,449 --> 00:12:31,939
- I like the 5.

217
00:12:31,984 --> 00:12:33,918
- Are you the third grade?

218
00:12:33,953 --> 00:12:35,545
- Yes.

219
00:12:35,588 --> 00:12:36,714
- What's your name?

220
00:12:36,756 --> 00:12:38,087
- Elmer Gravlaki.

221
00:12:38,124 --> 00:12:40,718
- Okay.
Thank you.

222
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:43,285
Sit down...please.

223
00:12:53,372 --> 00:12:55,306
Um...

224
00:12:55,341 --> 00:12:58,310
let's play a game.

225
00:13:01,280 --> 00:13:04,545
How about you say your name

226
00:13:04,583 --> 00:13:07,677
along with your favorite number?

227
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:09,051
[loud snap]
- Ow!

228
00:13:09,088 --> 00:13:10,077
He shot me!

229
00:13:10,122 --> 00:13:11,248
[laughter]

230
00:13:11,290 --> 00:13:13,224
It's not funny!

231
00:13:13,259 --> 00:13:14,954
- What's your name?

232
00:13:14,994 --> 00:13:16,427
- Danny O'Mazzi.

233
00:13:16,462 --> 00:13:18,794
- Danny, you can't shoot people
in the head,

234
00:13:18,831 --> 00:13:21,595
so go stand in the corner
and face the wall.

235
00:13:21,634 --> 00:13:22,601
- Cool.

236
00:13:22,635 --> 00:13:23,795
- No fair!

237
00:13:23,836 --> 00:13:25,497
Why does he get to stand
in the corner

238
00:13:25,538 --> 00:13:26,732
facing the wall?

239
00:13:26,772 --> 00:13:28,433
- Well, it's not supposed to be
a good thing.

240
00:13:28,474 --> 00:13:30,408
It's supposed to be
a punishment.

241
00:13:30,442 --> 00:13:33,070
- Miss Gray, I'm Rita Williams,
and I want you to know

242
00:13:33,112 --> 00:13:35,672
that Ellen always pees
when she gets nervous.

243
00:13:35,714 --> 00:13:37,614
She has a change of clothes
in a cubby

244
00:13:37,650 --> 00:13:40,016
in the nurse's office.

245
00:13:40,052 --> 00:13:42,816
- Go and do that, then, Ellen.

246
00:13:43,823 --> 00:13:46,223
- Miss Gray, I'm Lisa Venus,

247
00:13:46,258 --> 00:13:48,818
and my favorite number
is a billion.

248
00:13:48,861 --> 00:13:49,850
- What?

249
00:13:49,895 --> 00:13:52,489
- You told us to say our name
and our favorite number.

250
00:13:52,531 --> 00:13:54,692
- Yeah, get with the program.

251
00:13:54,733 --> 00:13:56,166
- And you are...

252
00:13:56,202 --> 00:13:57,692
- Ann DiGanno.

253
00:14:01,607 --> 00:14:07,136
- Lisa, how about choosing
a number between 1 and 9?

254
00:14:07,179 --> 00:14:08,840
- 9--I mean...

255
00:14:08,881 --> 00:14:10,576
2--
no, 7.

256
00:14:10,616 --> 00:14:12,311
- 7?

257
00:14:12,351 --> 00:14:14,717
- For sure 7.

258
00:14:14,753 --> 00:14:16,311
- Okay.

259
00:14:16,355 --> 00:14:18,550
Do I have any other volunteers?

260
00:14:18,591 --> 00:14:20,354
- Ooh, ooh, me, me.

261
00:14:20,392 --> 00:14:22,519
Oh, oh, me.
Pick me.

262
00:14:22,561 --> 00:14:24,085
My name is Levan Beeze,

263
00:14:24,129 --> 00:14:26,063
and my favorite number is 1.

264
00:14:26,098 --> 00:14:27,326
- Okay.

265
00:14:27,366 --> 00:14:30,563
Levan, you and Lisa

266
00:14:30,603 --> 00:14:34,596
come to the front and form
your numbers with your bodies.

267
00:14:37,409 --> 00:14:39,206
- What is this?

268
00:14:40,312 --> 00:14:43,941
- And what's the total
of Levan and Lisa?

269
00:14:43,983 --> 00:14:45,075
- 8.

270
00:14:45,117 --> 00:14:46,414
